Document: Renderers
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/renderers.rst
Summary: This section provides an overall comparison of Godot's Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+ renderers across various features, hardware requirements, target platforms, and capabilities.

Required hardware: Compatibility renderer is for older or low-end hardware. Mobile and Forward+ renderers are for newer or high-end hardware, requiring Vulkan, Direct3D 12, or Metal support. All renderers run on new hardware. Compatibility runs on old and low-end hardware, while Mobile runs on it but slower than Compatibility, and Forward+ is the slowest. Compatibility runs on hardware without RenderingDevice support, but Mobile and Forward+ do not.

Target platforms: Compatibility targets mobile, low-end desktop, and web. Mobile targets mobile and desktop. Forward+ targets desktop.
Desktop: All renderers support desktop.
Mobile: Compatibility supports low-end mobile. Mobile supports high-end mobile. Forward+ supports mobile but is poorly optimized; use Mobile or Compatibility instead.
XR: Compatibility supports XR and is recommended for standalone headsets. Mobile supports XR and is recommended for desktop headsets. Forward+ supports XR but is poorly optimized; use Mobile or Compatibility instead.
Web: Compatibility supports web. Mobile and Forward+ do not.
2D Games: All renderers support 2D games, but Compatibility is usually sufficient for 2D.
3D Games: All renderers support 3D games.

Feature set: Compatibility offers 2D and core 3D features. Mobile offers most rendering features. Forward+ offers all rendering features.
2D rendering features: All renderers support 2D rendering features.
Core 3D rendering features: All renderers support core 3D rendering features.
Advanced rendering features: Compatibility does not support advanced rendering features. Mobile supports them, but limited by mobile hardware. Forward+ supports all advanced rendering features.
New features: Some new rendering features are added to Compatibility, typically after Mobile and Forward+. Most new rendering features are added to Mobile, usually at the same time as Forward+. All new features are added to Forward+ first, as it is the focus of new development.

Rendering cost: Compatibility has a low base cost but high scaling cost. Mobile has a medium base cost and medium scaling cost. Forward+ has the highest base cost but low scaling cost.
Rendering driver: Compatibility uses OpenGL. Mobile and Forward+ use Vulkan, Direct3D 12, or Metal.
---CHUNK---
Document: Renderers
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/renderers.rst
Summary: This section compares light and shadow features across Godot's rendering backends: Forward, Mobile, and Forward+.

Lights and shadows. See Lights and shadows for more information.

*   Lighting approach: Forward (Forward), Forward (Mobile), Clustered Forward (Forward+).
*   Maximum OmniLights: 8 per mesh (Forward, can be increased), 8 per mesh and 256 per view (Mobile), 512 per cluster (Forward+, can be increased).
*   Maximum SpotLights: 8 per mesh (Forward, can be increased), 8 per mesh and 256 per view (Mobile), 512 per cluster (Forward+, can be increased).
*   Maximum DirectionalLights: 8 (Forward, Mobile, Forward+).
*   PCSS for OmniLight and SpotLight: Not supported (Forward), Supported (Mobile, Forward+).
*   PCSS for DirectionalLight: Not supported (Forward, Mobile), Supported (Forward+).
*   Light projector textures: Not supported (Forward), Supported (Mobile, Forward+).
---CHUNK---
Document: Global Illumination
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/renderers.rst
Summary: This section details the compatibility of various global illumination features across different Godot renderers.

Global Illumination. See introduction to global illumination for more information.
- ReflectionProbe (Compatibility): Supported, 2 per mesh.
- ReflectionProbe (Mobile): Supported, 8 per mesh.
- ReflectionProbe (Forward+): Supported, unlimited.
- LightmapGI (Compatibility): Rendering of baked lightmaps is supported. Baking requires hardware with RenderingDevice support.
- LightmapGI (Mobile): Supported.
- LightmapGI (Forward+): Supported.
- VoxelGI (Compatibility): Not supported.
- VoxelGI (Mobile): Not supported.
- VoxelGI (Forward+): Supported.
- Screen-Space Indirect Lighting (SSIL) (Compatibility): Not supported.
- Screen-Space Indirect Lighting (SSIL) (Mobile): Not supported.
- Screen-Space Indirect Lighting (SSIL) (Forward+): Supported.
- Signed Distance Field Global Illumination (SDFGI) (Compatibility): Not supported.
- Signed Distance Field Global Illumination (SDFGI) (Mobile): Not supported.
- Signed Distance Field Global Illumination (SDFGI) (Forward+): Supported.
---CHUNK---
Document: Environment and post-processing
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/renderers.rst
Summary: This section outlines the compatibility of various environment and post-processing features across different Godot renderers.

Environment and post-processing. See doc_environment_and_post_processing for more information.

Feature compatibility:
*   Fog (Depth and Height): Supported on Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+.
*   Volumetric Fog: Not supported on Compatibility or Mobile, supported on Forward+.
*   Tonemapping: Supported on Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+.
*   Screen-Space Reflections: Not supported on Compatibility or Mobile, supported on Forward+.
*   Screen-Space Ambient Occlusion (SSAO): Supported on Compatibility, not supported on Mobile, supported on Forward+.
*   Screen-Space Indirect Lighting (SSIL): Not supported on Compatibility or Mobile, supported on Forward+.
*   Signed Distance Field Global Illumination (SDFGI): Not supported on Compatibility or Mobile, supported on Forward+.
*   Glow: Supported on Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+.
*   Adjustments: Supported on Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+.
*   Custom post-processing with fullscreen quad: Supported on Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+.
*   Custom post-processing with CompositorEffects: Not supported on Compatibility, supported on Mobile and Forward+.
---CHUNK---
Document: Antialiasing
Path: godot/tutorials/rendering/renderers.rst
Summary: This section provides a compatibility matrix for various antialiasing features across Godot's Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+ renderers.

Antialiasing. See 3D antialiasing for more information.

Compatibility of antialiasing features across renderers:
*   MSAA 3D: Supported in Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+ renderers.
*   MSAA 2D: Not supported in Compatibility, but supported in Mobile and Forward+ renderers.
*   TAA: Not supported in Compatibility or Mobile, but supported in Forward+ renderer.
*   FSR2: Not supported in Compatibility or Mobile, but supported in Forward+ renderer.
*   FXAA: Not supported in Compatibility, but supported in Mobile and Forward+ renderers.
*   SMAA: Not supported in Compatibility, but supported in Mobile and Forward+ renderers.
*   SSAA: Supported in Compatibility, Mobile, and Forward+ renderers.
*   Screen-space roughness limiter: Not supported in Compatibility, but supported in Mobile and Forward+ renderers.
---CHUNK---
